               <msContents>
                  <summary>I) Sǝnkǝssar “Synaxarion” for the second half of the year (fols.
                     3ra-192vc)
 I-1) Maggābit (fols. 3ra-34va)
 I-2) Miyāzyā (fols.
                     34va-64rc)
 I-3) Gǝnbot (fols. 64va-97rb)
 I-4) Sane (fols.
                     97rb-123vb)
 I-5) Ḥamle (fols. 123vb-157vb)
 I-6) Naḥāse (fols.
                     157vc-183rb)
 I-7) Ṗagʷǝmen (fols. 183rb-189va)
 I-8) Fragment of
                     Ṗagʷǝmen (fols. 190ra-192vc)
 The commemorative notices are followed by
                     ʿarke-hymns
 
 Additio 1.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1">

                     <incipit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </incipit>
                     <explicit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </explicit>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
                  
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i2">
                     <note>ff. 1 and 2 are unruled.</note>
                     <colophon xml:id="coloph1">
                        <locus target="#189rc">189rc</locus>:<locus target="#189rc">189rc</locus>: The
                        colophon is written in Amharic. It tells that the scribe is Walda Giyorgis (his
                        baptismal name; his worldly mane is däbtära Fänta) of Säqʷäṭa Gabrǝʾel, who was
                        brought up by Wag sǝyyum Bǝrru, and that the exemplar was the Synaxarion of
                        Säqʷäṭa Gabrǝʾel. </colophon>
                  </msItem>
                  
